1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The Slav is one of black's most solid 
weapons against the Queen's Pawn. This Defence has been the favourite of many great 
players, especially World Champion Vassily Smyslov. It's not easy to gain an 
advantage against this variation, generally regarded as leading to extremely solid 
play. My suggestion aims to create some unbalanced play.} 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4 $5 {The 
main moves in this variation are 6. Ne5 and 6. e3. But the text move is very logical 
- white wants to capture the important light squared bishop and play with the center 
and the bishops pair. I have used this move very successfully. Now black has to 
decide if he allows this capture or not.} Bc8 {This retreat looks odd - why should 
black retreat the bishop so passively? And this move also shows that he is happy with 
a draw. But actually the knight is a bit clumsy on h4. That's why this is a very 
important move.} 7. e3 {Now black has two ways of playing. One of them is very 
creative and seldom played, but I believe it might become trendy. The other is the 
classical approach, leading to an isolated queen's pawn position.} e5 {This is the 
classical move.} 8. Bxc4 exd4 9. exd4 Be7 10. O-O O-O {We have a classical isolated 
queen's pawn position at the board. It's important to notice that black's pawn is on 
c6 and not on e6, as it is usually the case in other typical IQP positions (Panno 
Attack, for instance). This makes white's c4 bishop a exceptionally strong piece. 
Overall I believe white is slightly better here.} 11. Re1 Nd5 12. Nf3 Be6 13. Qb3 Na6 
14. Bd2 Nab4 15. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Bc3e4,Be4c5][%csl Bc5] A typical manoeuvre. The knight 
heads to c5.} Bf5 16. Ne5 a5 17. Nc5 $14 {[%cal Rb7b6][%csl Bc5,Rc6] Black's position 
is somewhat unpleasant. It's not easy to deal with the c5 knight. If black takes it, 
then white gets many important dark squares. If he black plays...b6 then white has 
tactical ideas with Nxc6.} *

