1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The Slav is one of black's most solid 
weapons against the Queen's Pawn. This Defence has been the favourite of many great 
players, especially World Champion Vassily Smyslov. It's not easy to gain an 
advantage against this variation, generally regarded as leading to extremely solid 
play. My suggestion aims to create some unbalanced play.} 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4 $5 {The 
main moves in this variation are 6. Ne5 and 6. e3. But the text move is very logical 
- white wants to capture the important light squared bishop and play with the center 
and the bishops pair. I have used this move very successfully. Now black has to 
decide if he allows this capture or not.} e6 7. Nxf5 exf5 {It might look strange to 
let white take the bishop at f5, gaining the bishops pair and doubling the black 
pawns. This position is however, totally classical and has been known since the days 
of Rubinstein and Alekhine.} 8. e3 {[%cal Rc1e3,Gf5e4][%csl Bc1,Bf1,Re3,Ge4,Gf8] The 
strategic elements of the position are very clear. White will have a very strong 
light squared bishop at c4. As compensation black has more space and good control of 
the central squares. Another problem is the c1 bishop, which looks very passive by 
now. The great question is whether white will be able to open the position and 
exploit the bishops pair. But first both sides need to finish the development.} Bb4 
{In the Slav, black's bishop usually goes to this square, where it controls the 
center indirectly, by pressing the c3 knight.} 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. Qc2 $1 {This is an 
important move. White attacks the f5 pawn and forces black to create some weaknesses 
after g6. The alternative is to advance the pawn with f4, but in this case the 
position opens.} f4 {is dubious:} 11. O-O fxe3 12. fxe3 {[%cal Bf1f8][%csl Bf8] and 
the change in the pawn structure favours white. Now it's easier to advance the center 
and attack down the'f' file.} *

