1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The Slav is one of black's most solid 
weapons against the Queen's Pawn. This Defence has been the favourite of many great 
players, especially World Champion Vassily Smyslov. It's not easy to gain an 
advantage against this variation, generally regarded as leading to extremely solid 
play. My suggestion aims to create some unbalanced play.} 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4 $5 {The 
main moves in this variation are 6. Ne5 and 6. e3. But the text move is very logical 
- white wants to capture the important light squared bishop and play with the center 
and the bishops pair. I have used this move very successfully. Now black has to 
decide if he allows this capture or not.} e6 7. Nxf5 exf5 {It might look strange to 
let white take the bishop at f5, gaining the bishops pair and doubling black pawns. 
This position is ideal, however, is totally classical, known since the days of 
Rubinstein and Alekhine.} 8. e3 {The strategic elements of the position are very 
clear. White will have a very strong light squared bishop at c4. As compensation 
black has more space and good control of the central squares. Another problem is the 
c1 bishop, which looks very passive by now. The great question is whether white will 
be able to open the position and exploit the bishops pair. But first both sides need 
to finish the development.} Bb4 {In the Slav black's bishop usually goes to this 
square, where it controls the center indirectly, by pressing the c3 knight.} 9. Bxc4 
O-O 10. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Bc2f5][%csl Bf5] This is an important move. White attacks the 
f5 pawn and forces black to create some weaknesses after g6. Instead of g6, black can 
advance the pawn with f4, but in this case the position opens.} g6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. 
f3 $1 {[%cal Bf3e4,Ge3e4,Gc2f2] A crucial move. White must prepare the opening of the 
center with e4, so that the bishops pair gets more scope. This is also helpful in 
order to avoid any knight jumps to e4 and also give the f2 square for the queen 
(sometimes white can go Qf2-h4) .} Rc8 {[%cal Gc2f2,Gc1d2,Ga1d1,Bd2e1,Be1h4,Re3e4] A 
useful move, since black's counterplay is related to the move...c6-c5. Black has 
other options too. I believe the most important thing is to understand white's 
available plans. We can go straight for a e4 push; it's possible to play Qf2-Bd2-Rad1 
and then prepare e4 again or simply play Bd2-Rad1 and then maybe Be1-h4. White will 
basically be doing one of this 3 plans in all positions.} 13. Kh1 {White must deploy 
some prophylaxis before trying to open the position. 13. e4 would to be too hasty due 
to Nb6!} c5 14. Ba2 {Another necessary prophylactic move.} a6 $5 {This mysterious 
move was played against me by Swedish GM Erik Blomqvist in the Baku Olympiad. Both 
sides are making a lot of cunning moves, waiting to see how the action develops. 
Black has many alternatives and we just have to remember white's 3 main plans: 1- 
dxc5 followed by e4, opening the position and leading to tactical play; 2- Qf2, Bd2, 
Rad1 and preparing e4; 3- Bd2-Rad1 and prepare e4 with Be1-h4 or Bc1.} 15. Bd2 $5 
{It's also possible to just to finish the development. However, any of white's 3 
major plans is possible.} Qb6 16. Rad1 {With a small advantage for white.} *

