[Comment "gm-rafael-leitaos-fight-the-slav-defense/course/3676, variation/118354"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The Slav is one of black's most solid 
weapons against the Queen's Pawn. This Defence has been the favourite of many great 
players, especially World Champion Vassily Smyslov. It's not easy to gain an 
advantage against this variation, generally regarded as leading to extremely solid 
play. My suggestion aims to create some unbalanced play.} 5. a4 Bf5 6. Nh4 $5 {The 
main moves in this variation are 6. Ne5 and 6. e3. But the text move is very logical 
- white wants to capture the important light squared bishop and play with the center 
and the bishops pair. I have used this move very successfully. Now black has to 
decide if he allows this capture or not.} e6 7. Nxf5 exf5 {It might look strange to 
let white take the bishop at f5, gaining the bishops pair and doubling black pawns. 
This position is ideal, however, is totally classical, known since the days of 
Rubinstein and Alekhine.} 8. e3 {The strategic elements of the position are very 
clear. White will have a very strong light squared bishop at c4. As compensation 
black has more space and good control of the central squares. Another problem is the 
c1 bishop, which looks very passive by now. The great question is whether white will 
be able to open the position and exploit the bishops pair. But first both sides need 
to finish the development.} Bb4 {In the Slav black's bishop usually goes to this 
square, where it controls the center indirectly, by pressing the c3 knight.} 9. Bxc4 
O-O 10. Qc2 $1 {This is an important move. White attacks the f5 pawn and forces black 
to create some weaknesses after g6. The alternative is to advance the pawn with f4, 
but in this case the position opens.} g6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. f3 $1 {A crucial move. 
White must prepare the opening of the center with e4, so that the bishops pair gets 
more scope. This is also helpful in order to avoid any knight jumps to e4 and also 
give the f2 square for the queen (sometimes white can go Qf2-h4) .} Qb6 13. Bd2 c5 
{Everytime black places a piece on b6 and doesn't secure it with a7-a5, we have to 
think about the possibility of playing a4-a5.} 14. a5 $1 Qd8 15. Nd5 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 
{[%csl Bc4,Rd7] even with some exchanges white keeps a clear advantage since the 
bishop is better than the knight in this open position.} *

