before trying to open the position. 13. e4 would to be too hasty due to Nb6!} c5 14. 
Ba2 {Another necessary prophylactic move.} Qe7 $10 {Again it is necessary to repeat 
that in general white has a choice of three plans: 1- taking on c5 and playing e4 (as 
we saw before); 2- play Qf2 and the Bd2, followed by Rad1 or e1; 3- play Bd2, 
followed by Rad1, leaving all options open, including Bd2-e1-h4. It's really hard to 
decide which is best. In this position I offer two approaches.} 15. Qf2 $5 Nb6 {A 
normal move. Accepting the pawn sacrifice would be suicide.} 16. e4 $146 {An 
important opening novelty.} cxd4 17. Qxd4 Rfd8 18. Qf2 {[%cal Bc1g5,Bg5e7][%csl Bf6] 
As usual white just sacrifices whatever is necessary to open the position. The idea 
is to play Bg5 and create a deadly pin.} Bxc3 19. bxc3 Nxa4 20. Bg5 Nxc3 21. Qh4 
{with a strong initiative. A nice line is:} Rc6 22. exf5 Nxa2 23. Rxa2 gxf5 24. Rc2 
$1 Re6 25. Re2 $1 Rdd6 26. Bh6 $1 {With a big advantage for white.} *

